WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.760
My name is Becca Krouse. I am a data scientist at GSK in our Statistics and Data Science

00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:20.320
Innovation Hub, where my team is working on building support systems and facilitating

00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:25.959
the adoption of R across biostatistics. Today I'll be talking about R Package Assessment

00:00:25.959 --> 00:00:34.759
lessons that can be learned from pharma. In today's world, we have no shortage of products

00:00:34.759 --> 00:00:40.480
right at our fingertips that can be received in just days or even hours with the click

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:46.959
of a mouse. Vendors of all shapes and sizes have the ability to reach consumers across

00:00:46.959 --> 00:00:53.520
the globe, which means as consumers we have a wide variety of features to choose from,

00:00:53.520 --> 00:01:02.959
but also quite a range of quality. Sound familiar? Whether you're looking for something

00:01:02.959 --> 00:01:08.800
you need on Amazon or a package on CRAN, you probably want to find something that suits

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:15.599
your needs that you can count on. So how do you make those decisions? What do you look

00:01:15.599 --> 00:01:22.800
for? You're probably going to look at indicators that you feel are important. So if you think

00:01:22.800 --> 00:01:29.480
about how you approach online shopping, you probably go to the reviews, the ratings, badges,

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:34.800
the name of the seller, and depending on what you're looking for, how much time you have,

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:41.440
maybe you deep dive into those reviews. While the indicators, and I'll say the indicators

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:47.160
give you an overall picture of confidence of whether the product is going to look, feel,

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:53.680
and perform as advertised. While the indicators are a little bit different for packages, the

00:01:53.680 --> 00:02:00.959
overall idea is the same. A little bit of research is going to go a long way to build

00:02:00.959 --> 00:02:07.239
that picture of confidence that the package is going to produce results that you can count

00:02:07.239 --> 00:02:17.479
on that are accurate. Now, this idea is absolutely critical to those of us in, I mean, it doesn't

00:02:17.479 --> 00:02:22.199
matter your work, but it's especially critical to those of us in regulated industries like

00:02:22.199 --> 00:02:28.600
pharma, where it's really important for us to deliver safe and effective drugs to patients

00:02:28.600 --> 00:02:37.800
as quickly as we can. And to do so, we need to make sure our data and our analysis, our

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:46.960
entire pipelines are free of errors and full of integrity. A huge part of our pipelines

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:52.160
is the software that's used to produce the results, transform the data, all that type

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:58.880
of stuff. We really want to do our research, and the regulators expect that we do our due

00:02:58.880 --> 00:03:06.800
diligence and make defensible choices. So regulators expect that our choices are defensible,

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:13.039
meaning that we want to do our due diligence and provide sufficient documentation of why

00:03:13.039 --> 00:03:21.399
we feel that our software, our packages work correctly and produce correct results.

00:03:21.399 --> 00:03:26.360
So let's think about that for a minute. How do we really know our results are correct?

00:03:26.360 --> 00:03:32.000
Well, one thing we can do is compare against a source of truth. That source of truth could

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:39.479
be your common sense, another programmer, another programming language, maybe a publication

00:03:39.479 --> 00:03:48.080
like a textbook even. And this is true regardless of whether using the latest and greatest R

00:03:48.080 --> 00:03:54.440
package or a SAS proc that's been around for decades. It's all the same idea, and we

00:03:54.440 --> 00:03:59.639
want to make sure that our results are going to be accurate for many scenarios we haven't

00:03:59.639 --> 00:04:06.080
encountered yet, many new data sets, new studies in the future.

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:11.440
We're in exciting times now, and pharma is making progress full speed ahead towards R

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:18.320
being a primary tool used in studies and submission work. Folks across the industry

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:26.239
are putting their heads together to align on a common philosophy for what it takes to

00:04:26.239 --> 00:04:33.779
ensure that our packages are accurate. In the R validation hub specifically, this philosophy

00:04:33.779 --> 00:04:40.000
focuses on a package assessment. And there's some principles and some ideas in place, but

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:45.679
it's up to the individual organizations to then implement it for themselves and really

00:04:45.679 --> 00:04:56.559
decide how much evidence is enough. At GSK, we're working hard on our own implementation,

00:04:56.559 --> 00:05:04.839
and we've settled on a set of guiding principles for how we think about package assessment.

00:05:04.839 --> 00:05:10.160
And I'll present those to you today as the domains of trustworthiness. There's five of

00:05:10.160 --> 00:05:17.380
them. Each one plays an important role in the overall assessment, and each one consists

00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:25.239
of a collection of things. Those things are sometimes quite easy to measure, quantifiable,

00:05:25.239 --> 00:05:30.839
but others are a little bit more nuanced, harder to measure, more subjective.

00:05:30.839 --> 00:05:38.359
So let's step through these now, beginning with the community domain. The purpose of

00:05:38.359 --> 00:05:46.040
this domain is to get an idea of how broadly used a package is in the community, how much

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:52.000
folks are enjoying it, how strong its roots are. So specifically, we can look at something

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:59.160
like downloads to get an idea of the volume of use to date, and that volume of use is

00:05:59.160 --> 00:06:04.000
an indicator of how much the package has been vetted in real-life scenarios, how much

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:10.440
it's been stress-tested. We are also interested in the overall trajectory of that use. Is

00:06:10.440 --> 00:06:16.279
it gaining traction? Is the package maintaining or declining for some reason? Maybe there's

00:06:16.279 --> 00:06:24.440
another package that's come along that's superseded it. We also want to look at how the community

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:31.519
relates to the package and its maintainers, both how the community relies on this package,

00:06:31.519 --> 00:06:39.200
depends on this package as part of other software or other materials like books, and also, going

00:06:39.200 --> 00:06:46.239
the opposite direction, how much the package maintainer has a vested interest in supporting

00:06:46.239 --> 00:06:55.359
the community and keeping up with the ever-evolving, many moving parts of the community.

00:06:55.359 --> 00:07:01.239
Now something to keep in mind is in an industry like pharma, we have some fairly specific

00:07:01.239 --> 00:07:06.760
needs. Maybe our packages that we are choosing are a little more niche, or we have some internal

00:07:06.760 --> 00:07:12.959
packages that we're using. So by nature, these are going to have a little bit smaller community

00:07:12.959 --> 00:07:19.880
user base, and that's okay. We have other domains to look at as well.

00:07:19.880 --> 00:07:27.760
With the authorship domain, we are doing some research to learn who the developers are.

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:33.079
What are their backgrounds, their experience? And really, does that experience, is that

00:07:33.079 --> 00:07:39.359
appropriate match for the complexity of the tool? We found this one to be fairly important

00:07:39.359 --> 00:07:47.399
for statistical packages where that level of expertise is quite high, quite specific.

00:07:47.399 --> 00:07:54.799
So some things that we look at here are the overall reputation, how the community regards

00:07:54.799 --> 00:08:01.200
this author as an expert in their field, as an R developer, and how much experience they

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:06.640
have in both those areas. So something you could look at is the other packages that that

00:08:06.640 --> 00:08:14.679
person or those individuals might have out there, and any specific qualifications, degrees,

00:08:14.679 --> 00:08:19.920
certificates, things like that, all round out to our picture of who these authors are

00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:26.079
and what their backgrounds are. And this domain is quite dependent on what you can find out

00:08:26.079 --> 00:08:34.320
there, which obviously varies from individual to individual. So it's important nonetheless.

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:42.880
Our next domain is the documentation domain, which here I intend to cover functionality

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:51.200
documentation. So what is the tool supposed to do? What is the intent? And what is the

00:08:51.200 --> 00:08:56.640
scope, what are the limits of that tool to help us understand what is appropriate use,

00:08:56.640 --> 00:09:03.559
what is responsible use? This is kind of a prerequisite to being able to prove accuracy.

00:09:03.559 --> 00:09:10.799
You need to understand in which cases your function is going to produce correct results.

00:09:10.799 --> 00:09:16.400
So documentation, we are all probably pretty familiar with looking around at help files,

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:24.200
vignettes, examples. So what we're after is, you know, do those things exist, but also

00:09:24.200 --> 00:09:30.159
what is their quality? How helpful and clear are they? What types of scenarios are covered?

00:09:30.159 --> 00:09:38.479
And then for the intended use, clear documentation of expected inputs, expected outputs. Really

00:09:38.479 --> 00:09:47.159
nice if edge case, the limits piece is covered in there. What might we want to watch out

00:09:47.159 --> 00:09:56.960
for when we're using this tool, for instance. And this leads us into the software development

00:09:56.960 --> 00:10:05.479
lifecycle domain, which we are aiming to capture the overall process for how the code

00:10:05.479 --> 00:10:15.559
develops and evolves over time. How it is cared for, essentially. With this one, first

00:10:15.559 --> 00:10:23.719
and foremost, we need transparency into what's happening. And luckily for us, this is increasingly

00:10:23.719 --> 00:10:30.359
easy with things like GitHub, which is pretty popular these days. Allows us to get a peek

00:10:30.359 --> 00:10:35.880
into what's going on, what kind of branching model is being used, how are things being

00:10:35.880 --> 00:10:41.679
worked on and merged in, and are there any what is the road map of the tool? Are there

00:10:41.679 --> 00:10:50.640
any critical open issues? All things we can look at just by peeking into that repository.

00:10:50.640 --> 00:10:58.400
And to get a sense of how well supported it is, we can also look at the activity. How

00:10:58.400 --> 00:11:05.559
quickly the code or how often the code is being worked on, issues being closed, releases

00:11:05.559 --> 00:11:13.599
to CRAN. And then any safeguards that are in place to protect the integrity of the code

00:11:13.599 --> 00:11:20.539
as it evolves. Protected branches, continuous checking, continuous testing, all to prevent

00:11:20.539 --> 00:11:28.900
against any bugs being introduced as this changes. Now, something to keep in mind is

00:11:28.900 --> 00:11:34.820
a package could have all the hallmarks of a good package here. But maybe it's really,

00:11:34.820 --> 00:11:41.460
really new. And it hasn't had a chance to work out some of the bugs. And, you know,

00:11:41.460 --> 00:11:46.419
we're not aware of those yet. And it hasn't been stress tested enough yet. Or it's changing

00:11:46.419 --> 00:11:51.940
a lot. On the other end of things, a package could have fairly stalled development, which

00:11:51.940 --> 00:11:57.179
could mean it's been abandoned or it could mean it's just really, really stable. So something

00:11:57.179 --> 00:12:02.859
to keep in mind in looking at this domain is what is the history of the project? Where

00:12:02.859 --> 00:12:10.700
is it in terms of its life cycle? And our final domain is the testing domain.

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:16.619
So here, testing, I mean the actual testing inside the package. Oftentimes this is your

00:12:16.619 --> 00:12:22.219
test that, your unit tests. And what these do is check that the functionality is working

00:12:22.219 --> 00:12:31.179
as expected and that it's producing correct results. Which sounds a lot like our definition

00:12:31.179 --> 00:12:37.260
of accuracy that we talked about earlier. So a really solid test suite can be essentially

00:12:37.260 --> 00:12:44.739
a gold standard for how you can prove accuracy. So let's take a look at what we might look

00:12:44.739 --> 00:12:52.219
for inside the package. So this is your package directory. But we can look at whether a test

00:12:52.219 --> 00:12:58.020
exists and what they're covering. So things like code coverage. Which functions are being

00:12:58.020 --> 00:13:04.820
covered? And to what extent? And from there, we can look specifically at what we're interested

00:13:04.820 --> 00:13:10.780
in. What are the key things that we feel we are going to be using the most? And how

00:13:10.780 --> 00:13:16.900
deep that testing is on those. So what types of scenarios are covered there? What types

00:13:16.900 --> 00:13:25.700
of inputs are the developers looking for? And are they comparing against some known

00:13:25.700 --> 00:13:33.580
value? Even better if that source of truth comes from some outside resource.

00:13:33.580 --> 00:13:38.580
And I recognize this is a fairly technical task. So this may look a little bit different

00:13:38.580 --> 00:13:44.299
depending on who you are and what resources you have. But even being familiar with the

00:13:44.299 --> 00:13:51.739
first two, the presence, the breadth, and then taking a peek into the depth. Maybe some

00:13:51.739 --> 00:13:58.099
of those descriptions in the test that can be very helpful. Another thing to keep in

00:13:58.099 --> 00:14:04.419
mind about the testing domain is not everything is super easy to test. Sometimes visualizations

00:14:04.419 --> 00:14:11.140
or complex algorithms can be a little bit� really novel complex algorithms can be a little

00:14:11.140 --> 00:14:17.219
bit tougher to test. So that's okay. It's just� you know, again, we have the rest

00:14:17.219 --> 00:14:26.460
of the domains. So with those in mind, the assessment may

00:14:26.619 --> 00:14:34.419
look a little bit different depending on who you are and what you do. For us, we are very

00:14:34.419 --> 00:14:41.820
much working towards our submission work. We're very risk averse in this situation.

00:14:41.820 --> 00:14:50.179
We do a pretty in-depth assessment. So, you know, if you're just kind of poking around

00:14:50.179 --> 00:14:54.940
exploring, maybe you do a little bit lighter of an assessment. But getting to know your

00:14:54.940 --> 00:15:02.500
packages is really important. It will serve you well.

00:15:02.500 --> 00:15:09.260
Also on a task level, if you're transforming the data, changing the data in some way, or

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:17.099
performing a statistical analysis, the stakes might be a little bit higher if something

00:15:17.099 --> 00:15:23.219
goes awry as compared to� and also it might be harder to tell when something goes awry

00:15:23.219 --> 00:15:29.580
as compared to something that's more aesthetic in nature. So, again, your approach to the

00:15:29.580 --> 00:15:40.260
assessment might change depending on that. And so you could also perform this whole assessment

00:15:40.260 --> 00:15:47.260
and not be quite satisfied with the result. But maybe you have only one option. And this

00:15:47.260 --> 00:15:53.099
is the package you need. So maybe you're willing to bend a little bit on your risk and build

00:15:53.179 --> 00:16:03.460
some extra safeguards around that for yourself. Augment it with some testing or extra QC.

00:16:03.460 --> 00:16:11.260
So even if you find yourself in the left side, very much in the stable risk averse, the rest

00:16:11.260 --> 00:16:16.900
of the ecosystem is going to continue to evolve and change. And that's the beauty of R, right?

00:16:16.900 --> 00:16:23.700
There's cutting edge newer things every single day. So it's important for us, you know, if

00:16:23.700 --> 00:16:29.260
we are in that situation, to keep our eyes up ahead of what's to come. And find ways

00:16:29.260 --> 00:16:36.500
to innovate. Find ways to experiment. And keep our minds open for any gems that come

00:16:36.500 --> 00:16:42.500
along. And we can in turn then grow our tried and true collection of packages that we count

00:16:42.500 --> 00:16:53.099
on. All right. So I said there were five domains. But I'm going to throw you one more.

00:16:53.099 --> 00:17:00.979
Which is the domain about thinking holistically. So when we do these assessments, we are not

00:17:00.979 --> 00:17:09.099
expecting a perfect score by any means. The packages the purpose of the assessment is

00:17:09.099 --> 00:17:14.660
to allow these packages to shine where they are strong. And let those strengths or weaknesses

00:17:14.660 --> 00:17:22.219
guide us in the rest of our assessment. And help us focus in on what matters. So for instance,

00:17:22.219 --> 00:17:28.699
a package could have really strong tests. But maybe not as much community support or

00:17:28.699 --> 00:17:36.180
vice versa. So these things can kind of counter each other, right? So if we're flexible and

00:17:36.180 --> 00:17:44.140
adaptable in our approach, then we can more effectively collect that body of evidence

00:17:44.140 --> 00:17:49.500
that's going to inform our sense of trust in this wonderfully imperfect open source

00:17:49.500 --> 00:17:51.300
world. Thank you.

